  "text": "The basic operating principle behind an electrochemical sensor relies on the transfer of electrons between an electrode and a chemical redox reaction. A thorough handling of the principles underlying electrochemical sensors can be found in [CITATION_1] . One of the most successful electrochemical sensors for detecting metabolic products is the Clark-type oxygen sensor, which uses an electrode (usually made of platinum or palladium) to catalyze the reduction (or gain of electrons) of oxygen and water",
